Summary

Using the bodies of text samples provided by Coursera I am building an app to predict what the next word will be when the beginning of a phrase is entered. In this exploratory analysis I will share information about the data, my initial findings and my plans of how to move forward with the app.

The Data

Coursera provides all of the data here:
https://d396qusza40orc.cloudfront.net/dsscapstone/dataset/Coursera-SwiftKey.zip
I am only taking the en_US sub-directory into consideration. If we look at all the data we see that it is massive:

## [1] "The Twitter data has 2360148 rows and 30093369 words."
## [1] "The blog data has 899288 rows and 37546246 words."
## [1] "The news data has 1010242 rows and 34762395 words."

Since these are so massive, I took a 1% sample of each for exploration. This brings the size of our data to a lot more manageable size:

## [1] "The Twitter sample has 23601 rows and 301414 words."
## [1] "The blog sample has 8993 rows and 370203 words."
## [1] "The news sample has 10102 rows and 340461 words."

Data Prep

Since this app will be used to predict the next word, we arent going to want to suggest profanity (at least without the user opting into it). So for the analysis I removed everything from this fantastic list:
https://github.com/shutterstock/List-of-Dirty-Naughty-Obscene-and-Otherwise-Bad-Words/blob/master/en

I also dropped all twitter handles, hastags, and RT:s since predicting them seems outside the scope of this project. I have also removed unicode characters and numbers to focus on text.

While capitalization, punctuation, and their full form may play an important role when predicting, for now I am converting everything to lower case, removing punctuation, and stemming the words. In text analysis it is common to remove stop words (the most commonly used words in a language) however for our purposes they will likely be the words we are using and predicting the most. So I am exploring both with them and without.

Interesting Findings

Unigrams

There are many, many, more words that are used rarely than those that are used extremely frequently. This pulls the histogram so far towards low numbers that the high frequency words arent even visible.

To highlight how many words are used only a handful of times and how frequently the most common words are used in a more visible way, I plotted the amount of times each frequency occurs.

If we look at the top twenty most commonly used words and their occurrences, we can see just how dominate the most common stop words are. Even compared to the top 50 most used words, the and and tower over the rest of the words.

Plans for prediction algorithm and app

A few things to improve data integrity:

  • Check for repetitive long n-grams (are likely bad to keep if they are just boilerplate items in blogs or news).

  • Consider remove duplicate tweets since if they are just copies their phrases arent actually more common.

  • Once everything is working use a larger sample than 1% and see if it improves results.

For the algorithm:

  • Figure out how to spit the last word off all the n-grams and find probability of what word will follow it.

  • Turn that into a marcov chain to use when predicting the next word.

  • Learn more about back off models and smoothing algorithms since they both sound like they will lead to better predictions.

  • Possibly figure out how to include profanity in the marcov chains, so that we can predict more accurately, but not suggest it (without them opting in to such a thing.)

The app

  • Hopefully this part will be pretty straightforward once everything else is done. I am planning to just return the most likely answer when text is entered by the user. If its possible to do so fast enough, I would love to return the top three most likely next words.

  • It would also be cool to log the users entries above where they type, so that they can do multiple sentences/entries and see them all.

  • If simple enough, it would be interesting to let user choose to have profanity predicted or not.
